    "Evaluation": {
      "text": "Must distinguish from\nscleritis\nScleritis likely to have pain and decreased vision\nUse of 2.5% phenylephrine drops will cause vasoconstriction/blanching of episcleral but not scleral vessels. Thus, there will be decreased injection and redness in episcleritis but not scleritis.\n[2]\nRed area will be mobile if moved with a moist q-tip\nMust distinguish from\nconjunctivitis\nEpiscleritis will usually have a sectoral pattern of injection, as opposed to a diffuse injection seen in conjunctivitis.",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "scleritis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Scleritis"
        },
        {
          "text": "conjunctivitis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Conjunctivitis"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Management": {
      "text": "Topical lubricants\nArtificial tears q4-6hr\nOral\nNSAIDs\nTopical steroids\nmay relieve symptoms but are associated with rebound redness and potentially worse future events and are generally not recommended\n[3]",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "NSAIDs",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/NSAIDs"
        },
        {
          "text": "Topical steroids",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Topical_steroids"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Disposition": {
      "text": "Refer to ophtho is unsure of diagnosis or if steroids are necessary for treatment\nSelf-limiting (will resolve within 2-3 weeks)",
